   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <opener>
               <pb n="1*"/>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>To Baron W.<hi rend="superscript">m</hi> von Humboldt</addrLine>
               </address>
               <dateline>[May 25. 1835]</dateline>
               <lb/>Sir –</opener>
            <p>I send you by my friend <persName ref="gticknor">George Ticknor Esq.<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
               </persName> (to whom I have given a letter of
                    introduction to you) two little Indian publications – 1. <bibl sameAs="134">A
                        short Sermon &amp; Hymns, in the Muskokee or Creek language</bibl>; 2. A
                    Cherokee Alphabet published in a large size for the use of the Indian
                        children.<note type="footnote" resp="editor">Wahrscheinlich ist damit die 42,8 ×
                        37,1 cm große Tafel gemeint, die 1835 in Boston bei Pendleton’s Lithography
                        gedruckt wurde, siehe James Constantine Pilling (1888): <hi rend="italic">Bibliography of the Iroquoian Languages</hi>, Washington: Government
                        Printing Office, <ref type="linkExt"
                       target="https://books.google.de/books?id=2kkSAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=RA5-PA72&amp;lpg=RA5-PA72&amp;dq=cherokee+alphabet+pendleton%27s+lithography&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=1k9a8j3Tae&amp;sig=ACfU3U1GUrGA76cjzqrvAmtvW9lCGIVTfw&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwj_qpeD7-DqAhXS3KQKHf9BCqwQ6AEwGnoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&amp;q=cherokee%20alphabet%20pendleton's%20lithography&amp;f=false">S. 72 s.v. Guess (George)</ref> mit Abb. [FZ]</note>
            </p>
            <p>I have been obliged to intermit my Indian studies for nearly three years past, in
                    consequence of being employed by the government of this state, with two others
                    of my profession, in the redaction of the laws of our state in order to reduce
                    them to a code. We have now almost completed this laborious task, after which I
                    hope to find a little leisure for other studies</p>
            <p>I avail myself of this occasion to acknowledge the receipt of your obliging
                    letter of the <date when="1834-12-08">8.<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> Dec.<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> last</date> which arrived two months ago, but
                    to which my pressing engagements abovementioned <add>have not</add> permitted me
                    to reply.</p>
            <p>I am much flattered by your friendly request to prepare a memoir upon the subject
                    of the Indian languages; but I feel conscious that you estimate too highly my
                    ability to do justice to the subject. I shall not, however, <pb n="2*"/> lose
                    sight of this object; &amp; I may add, that our stock of materials is daily
                    increasing. Our Missionaries are indefatigable, &amp; study various dialects
                    with zeal. One of them <persName ref="cbyington">Mr. Byington</persName>, has
                    nearly, or quite, completed two very important works – a Dictionary &amp;
                    Grammar of the language of the Choctaws,<note type="footnote" resp="editor">Die
                        beiden Werke sind erst Jahrzehnte später publiziert worden; siehe James
                        Constantine Pilling (1885): <hi rend="italic">Proof-Sheets of a Bibliography
                            of the Languages of the North American Indians</hi>, Washington:
                        Government Printing Office, <ref type="linkExt"
                       target="https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/97785#page/161/mode/1up">S. 111 zu Nr. 557–561</ref>. [FZ]</note> now more
                    correctly called <hi rend="underline">Chahtas</hi>. Our Scholars are impatient
                    to see your great work on the languages of this continent. I hope no accident
                    has impeded its progress. I am also extremely desirous to see <bibl sameAs="227">your work on the ancient political language of the island of Java</bibl>;
                    the General Introduction which you make to it<note type="footnote" resp="editor">D.h. die "Kawi-Einleitung". [FZ]</note>, on the languages of the Globe
                    will be of the highest interest &amp; importance to philologists.</p>
            <p>When I read your last letter, I was sorry to learn that your health was not yet
                        reestablis<supplied cert="high">hed.</supplied>
               <note type="footnote" resp="editor">Papierbruch.</note> I hope this is no longer the case<note type="footnote" resp="editor">Humboldt war bereits am 8. April 1835 in Tegel gestorben. [FZ]</note>, and
                    that your physical strength will enable you still to employ your eminent
                    intellectual powers in the advancement of those branches of knowledge to which
                    you have so largely contributed –</p>
            <closer>
               <salute>I am &amp;.<hi rend="superscript">c</hi>
               </salute>
               <lb/>
               <dateline>Boston May 25.<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1835</dateline>
            </closer>
         </div>
